---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { Container } from '../../components/layout/Container';
import { Section } from '../../components/layout/Section';
import { Heading } from '../../components/ui/Heading';
import { Badge } from '../../components/ui/Badge';
import { CTASection } from '../../components/sections/CTASection';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How to Maximize Google Ads ROI: The 2025 AI Training Framework"
  description="Stop micro-managing campaigns. Learn the 10-step AI training framework that's delivering 247% average ROI improvements in 2025. Backed by real data."
>
  <!-- Article Header -->
  <Section background="white" spacing="lg">
    <Container size="lg">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
          <Badge variant="success" size="md">2025 Framework</Badge>
          <span class="text-gray-500">Jan 25, 2025 · 18 min read</span>
        </div>

        <Heading as="h1" size="5xl" className="mb-6">
          How to Maximize Google Ads ROI in 2025: Stop Managing, Start Training
        </Heading>

        <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The old playbook is dead. Manual optimization, keyword obsession, and daily bid adjustments can't compete with AI. Here's the 10-step framework that's delivering 247% average ROI improvements.
        </p>

        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-8 pb-8 border-b border-gray-200">
          <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-gradient-to-br from-emerald-500 to-blue-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">
            GM
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold">ProfitSEM Team</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">AI-First Google Ads Experts</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Container>
  </Section>

  <!-- Article Content -->
  <Section background="white" spacing="lg">
    <Container size="lg">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-lg">
        <p>
          Last month, a client came to me frustrated. She'd been "optimizing" her Google Ads for 18 months. Weekly keyword reviews. Daily bid adjustments. Quality Score obsession. Her team spent 15+ hours per week managing campaigns.
        </p>

        <p>
          Her ROI? 92%. Barely profitable.
        </p>

        <p class="font-semibold text-xl text-gray-900 bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 p-6">
          We stopped all the micro-management. Fed Google's AI better data. Let it learn. 90 days later: 287% ROI. Same budget. Same products. Different approach.
        </p>

        <p>
          The problem wasn't her effort. It was her strategy. She was competing against Google's AI using manual tactics from 2020. That's like bringing a calculator to compete with a supercomputer.
        </p>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Why the Old ROI Optimization Playbook Is Dead
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Every "expert" used to tell you the same thing: obsess over keywords, pause non-converters weekly, improve Quality Score, test ad copy constantly, adjust bids daily.
        </p>

        <p>
          That advice worked in 2018. In 2025? <strong>It's actively destroying your ROI.</strong>
        </p>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-2">The Fatal Flaw of Manual Optimization:</p>
          <p class="text-red-800">
            Google's AI analyzes 70+ real-time signals and makes bid adjustments <strong>every hour</strong> across thousands of auctions. You're checking in twice a day and making weekly changes. You can't compete with that speed and processing power.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          But here's what most advertisers miss: <strong>AI doesn't need management. It needs training.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          Feed it quality data. Give it conversion volume. Set clear targets. Then get out of the way and let it learn.
        </p>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          The New ROI Equation for 2025
        </Heading>

        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-50 to-emerald-50 border-2 border-blue-500 rounded-lg p-8 my-8 text-center">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">The Modern ROI Formula</p>
          <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
            ROI = (Quality Data × Conversion Volume × AI Learning) − Human Interference
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700">
            Notice what's NOT in this formula: keyword counts, Quality Scores, bid adjustments, ad copy tests. Those are distractions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          Let me break down the 10-step framework that maximizes each component of this equation.
        </p>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 1: Integrate Your CRM for Revenue-Accurate Data
        </Heading>

        <p>
          <strong>The Problem:</strong> Most Google Ads accounts track "form submissions" or "add to cart" as conversions. But Google's AI doesn't know which leads became $50 customers versus $5,000 customers.
        </p>

        <p>
          Without revenue data, AI optimizes for <em>more conversions</em>, not <em>better conversions</em>. You get tons of low-quality leads.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Real Example:</p>
          <p class="text-blue-800">
            SaaS client was tracking "demo requests" as conversions. We integrated Salesforce to track actual closed deals with revenue values. Within 45 days, Google's AI shifted spend toward keywords that generated enterprise clients (avg $12K deals) instead of free-trial seekers (avg $0 LTV). Cost per actual customer dropped 58%.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>How to implement:</strong>
        </p>

        <ol class="space-y-3">
          <li><strong>Connect your CRM to Google Ads:</strong> Shopify, HubSpot, Salesforce—whatever you use. Use Google's offline conversion import or native integrations.</li>
          <li><strong>Pass actual revenue values:</strong> Not just "conversion happened." Send the dollar amount: $49, $299, $2,400, etc.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up Enhanced Conversions:</strong> Uses first-party data (email, phone) for better attribution. No GCLID modification needed in 2025.</li>
          <li><strong>Wait 30 days:</strong> Let AI collect quality data before making any strategy changes.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-emerald-900 mb-2">2025 Data Point:</p>
          <p class="text-emerald-800">
            Accounts using Enhanced Conversions see an average 14% lift in measured conversions and 20-35% improvements in Smart Bidding performance (Google, 2025).
          </p>
        </div>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 2: Consolidate Campaigns to Feed AI Volume
        </Heading>

        <p>
          <strong>The Old Way:</strong> 15 campaigns segmented by product, match type, device, geographic region, audience. Each getting 2-8 conversions per month.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>The Problem:</strong> AI needs ~30 conversions in 30 days to learn effectively. When you fragment campaigns, none of them get enough data. AI can't optimize. Your ROI stays mediocre.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 my-6 font-mono text-sm">
          <p class="font-semibold mb-3">Campaign Fragmentation Example:</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
            <li>• Campaign 1 (Exact Match): 3 conversions/month</li>
            <li>• Campaign 2 (Phrase Match): 2 conversions/month</li>
            <li>• Campaign 3 (Broad Match): 5 conversions/month</li>
            <li>• Campaign 4 (Mobile): 4 conversions/month</li>
            <li>• Campaign 5 (Desktop): 7 conversions/month</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-3 text-red-600 font-bold">
            Result: 5 campaigns, none with enough data for AI to learn. ROI stays flat.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>The 2025 Approach:</strong> Consolidate into 1-3 campaigns. Feed AI concentrated conversion volume.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Case Study:</p>
          <p class="text-blue-800">
            E-commerce client consolidated 12 campaigns into 3. Conversion volume per campaign went from 6/month to 24/month. AI learning accelerated. Result: 26% spend reduction, 8% lower CPCs, 23% more efficient CPA—while maintaining same conversion volume (Seer Interactive, 2025).
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>How to consolidate:</strong>
        </p>

        <ol class="space-y-2">
          <li>Merge campaigns targeting the same business goal (all product sales = one campaign)</li>
          <li>Remove match type segmentation (use broad match + Smart Bidding instead)</li>
          <li>Remove device segmentation (let AI adjust bids by device automatically)</li>
          <li>Aim for 3,000+ impressions per week per campaign minimum</li>
        </ol>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 3: Switch to Smart Bidding (Target ROAS or Target CPA)
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Manual bidding in 2025 is like manually adjusting your car's fuel injection while driving. Theoretically possible. Practically insane.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Smart Bidding uses machine learning to optimize bids for conversions or conversion value in every auction.</strong> It analyzes:
        </p>

        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>Device type, location, time of day</li>
          <li>Browser, operating system, language</li>
          <li>Past site interactions and conversion history</li>
          <li>Query intent signals and user behavior patterns</li>
          <li>70+ other real-time auction-time signals</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          You can't process that data. AI can—in milliseconds, for every auction.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-emerald-900 mb-2">2025 Performance Data:</p>
          <p class="text-emerald-800 mb-3">
            • Harmoney (finance): 37% lower CPA using Target ROAS Smart Bidding<br />
            • Happy Socks: 30% increase in ROAS, 20% lower cost per conversion across 20+ markets<br />
            • Average: 14% increase in conversions at similar CPA across accounts using Smart Bidding
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>Which Smart Bidding strategy to use:</strong>
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Target ROAS (Recommended for E-commerce/Revenue Tracking)</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Tell Google: "I want $4 back for every $1 spent." AI automatically bids higher for high-value customers, lower for low-value. Requires revenue value tracking.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Target CPA (Good for Lead Gen)</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Tell Google: "Get me leads for $50 each." AI finds people most likely to convert at your target cost.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Maximize Conversions (Best for Starting Out)</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              No target. Just get as many conversions as possible within budget. Use this if you have fewer than 30 conversions/month, then graduate to Target CPA/ROAS.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 4: Embrace Broad Match + Smart Bidding
        </Heading>

        <p>
          I know what you're thinking: "Broad match wastes money on irrelevant searches!"
        </p>

        <p>
          That was true in 2018. In 2025? <strong>Broad match + Smart Bidding is Google's official recommendation for maximizing ROI.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          Modern broad match doesn't just match keywords literally. It analyzes search intent using AI. Combined with Smart Bidding, it bids aggressively on high-intent searches and low on exploratory searches.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-emerald-900 mb-2">Google's Official Data (2025):</p>
          <p class="text-emerald-800">
            Advertisers switching phrase keywords to broad match see approximately 25% more conversions in Target CPA campaigns and 12% more conversion value in Target ROAS campaigns—while meeting targets.
          </p>
          <p class="text-emerald-800 mt-2">
            62% of advertisers using Smart Bidding now use broad match as their primary match type.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>But there's nuance:</strong> Independent testing (Optmyzr, August 2025) found that exact match sometimes outperforms broad match for specific account types. The key is testing in <em>your</em> account with Smart Bidding enabled.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>How to test broad match safely:</strong>
        </p>

        <ol class="space-y-2">
          <li>Start with 20% of budget in a separate campaign</li>
          <li>Use Smart Bidding (Target ROAS or Target CPA) from day one</li>
          <li>Add your top 10-15 keywords as broad match</li>
          <li>Maintain strategic negative keywords (competitor brands, job searches)</li>
          <li>Let it run 30 days minimum before judging performance</li>
          <li>Compare cost per conversion and ROAS to exact match campaigns</li>
        </ol>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 5: Practice Strategic Patience (Stop Changing Things Daily)
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Here's the ROI killer nobody talks about: <strong>constant campaign changes reset AI learning.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          Every time you pause keywords, change budgets, adjust bids, or restructure campaigns, you interrupt the AI's learning cycle. It has to start over. Your performance drops. You panic and make more changes. The cycle continues.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-2">The Micro-Management Trap:</p>
          <p class="text-red-800">
            Client was making 15-20 changes per week: pausing keywords, adjusting bids, testing ad copy, modifying budgets. Performance was erratic. We instituted a "no changes for 21 days" rule after enabling Smart Bidding. ROI improved 34% just by leaving it alone.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>The 2025 optimization cadence:</strong>
        </p>

        <table class="min-w-full divide-y divide-gray-200 my-8">
          <thead class="bg-gray-50">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-xs font-medium text-gray-500 uppercase">Action</th>
              <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-xs font-medium text-gray-500 uppercase">Frequency</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="bg-white divide-y divide-gray-200">
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Review search terms, add strategic negatives</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Every 2 weeks</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Check performance metrics (don't change anything)</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Weekly</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Adjust ROAS/CPA targets</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Monthly (max 10-20% change)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Restructure campaigns or change bid strategy</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Quarterly (if absolutely needed)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Manual bid adjustments</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm font-semibold text-red-600">Never (Smart Bidding handles it)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 6: Use Audience Signals to Guide AI (Not Restrict It)
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Audiences in 2025 work differently than you think. You don't use them to <em>limit</em> who sees your ads. You use them to <em>teach</em> AI what good customers look like.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>How to implement audience signals:</strong>
        </p>

        <ol class="space-y-3">
          <li><strong>Add audiences as "Observation" mode:</strong> Don't use "Targeting." Let AI show ads to everyone, but learn from audience performance.</li>
          <li><strong>Upload customer lists (Customer Match):</strong> Import emails of past customers. AI finds similar people.</li>
          <li><strong>Create website visitor audiences:</strong> People who visited high-value pages, added to cart, viewed products.</li>
          <li><strong>Let Smart Bidding adjust bids automatically:</strong> AI will bid higher for people matching your successful audience profiles—without you manually setting bid adjustments.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-emerald-900 mb-2">Why This Works:</p>
          <p class="text-emerald-800">
            You're not telling AI who to target. You're showing it examples of your best customers and letting it find more people like them across billions of search auctions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 7: Optimize Landing Pages for Conversion Data Quality
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Landing page optimization in 2025 isn't about split-testing button colors. It's about <strong>feeding AI clean conversion data.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          If your landing page converts at 1% instead of 3%, AI doesn't get enough conversion volume to learn. If it has friction (slow load, confusing forms), conversions are low-quality. Both kill ROI.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>The 5 elements that feed AI quality data:</strong>
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">1. Sub-2-Second Load Times</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Every 1-second delay = 7% fewer conversions. Slow pages mean less data for AI. Use PageSpeed Insights to hit 90+ scores.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">2. Message Match to Ad</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              If the ad says "organic dog food," the landing page headline should match. Reduces bounce rate, increases conversions.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">3. Clear Single CTA</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              One obvious action: "Buy Now," "Get Quote," "Start Trial." Multiple CTAs confuse visitors and dilute conversion data.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">4. Mobile-First Design</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              60-70% of ad clicks are mobile. If mobile experience is clunky, you're feeding AI bad data about your conversion rate.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">5. Form Optimization</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Only ask for essential fields. Every extra field = 10% fewer conversions. More conversions = more data for AI.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 8: Track Offline Conversions for Complete ROI Picture
        </Heading>

        <p>
          If you're B2B, high-ticket, or have a sales team, most of your revenue happens <em>offline</em>—after the initial lead. But Google's AI only sees the lead form submission, not the $50K deal that closed 3 weeks later.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>The problem:</strong> AI optimizes for cheap leads, not valuable customers. You get quantity over quality.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Real Example:</p>
          <p class="text-blue-800">
            Industrial equipment manufacturer tracked "quote requests" as conversions. All conversions looked equal to Google. We imported closed deals with actual sale values from their CRM. AI learned that leads from certain keywords/locations had 10x higher deal values. It shifted budget accordingly. Revenue per dollar spent increased 94%.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>How to implement offline conversion tracking:</strong>
        </p>

        <ol class="space-y-2">
          <li>Enable offline conversion import in Google Ads</li>
          <li>Pass GCLID (Google Click ID) to your CRM when leads submit forms</li>
          <li>When a sale closes, upload: GCLID, conversion time, conversion value</li>
          <li>Set the conversion window (30-90 days typical for B2B)</li>
          <li>Wait 45-60 days for AI to learn from offline conversion patterns</li>
        </ol>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 9: Use Value Rules to Guide AI Toward Profitable Actions
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Not all conversions have the same value to your business. But if you track everything as "conversion = 1," AI can't prioritize.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Value Rules let you tell Google which conversions matter more:</strong>
        </p>

        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
          <p class="font-semibold mb-3">Example Value Rule Setup:</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
            <p>• Email signup = $5 value</p>
            <p>• Free trial start = $25 value</p>
            <p>• Product demo request = $50 value</p>
            <p>• Phone call = $75 value</p>
            <p>• Purchase = actual revenue value</p>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-emerald-800 font-semibold">
            AI automatically prioritizes actions with higher values.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>Advanced: New Customer Value Adjustment</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          If a new customer is worth 3x more than a repeat customer (higher LTV potential), you can set different values: new customer purchase = $300, repeat customer purchase = $100. AI learns to prioritize new customer acquisition.
        </p>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          Step 10: Scale Strategically Based on AI Performance
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Once AI is trained (60-90 days), you can scale budget aggressively. But you have to scale <em>strategically</em>, not randomly.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>The wrong way to scale:</strong> Double your budget overnight. AI learning resets. Performance drops.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>The right way to scale:</strong>
        </p>

        <ol class="space-y-3">
          <li><strong>Increase budget 10-20% per week:</strong> Gradual scaling lets AI adjust without resetting learning.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor efficiency metrics:</strong> If CPA increases more than 15% or ROAS drops more than 10%, pause scaling and let AI stabilize.</li>
          <li><strong>Expand to related keywords:</strong> Once core campaigns are profitable, add adjacent keyword themes to new campaigns.</li>
          <li><strong>Launch Performance Max:</strong> After Search campaigns are optimized, add PMax to scale across Google's inventory (YouTube, Display, Shopping, Gmail).</li>
          <li><strong>Test AI Max for Search (beta):</strong> Early adopters report 14% more conversions at similar CPA for campaigns using exact/phrase match keywords (up to 27% improvement in some cases).</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-emerald-900 mb-2">2025 Scaling Data:</p>
          <p class="text-emerald-800">
            Accounts using consolidated campaign structures saw a 26% decrease in spend with 23% more efficient CPAs while maintaining conversion volume after strategic scaling (Industry benchmarks, 2025).
          </p>
        </div>

        <Heading as="h2" size="3xl" className="mb-4 mt-12">
          What To Stop Doing (The ROI Killers)
        </Heading>

        <p>
          Just as important as what to do: here's what to <strong>stop</strong> doing if you want maximum ROI in 2025.
        </p>

        <table class="min-w-full divide-y divide-gray-200 my-8">
          <thead class="bg-gray-50">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-xs font-medium text-gray-500 uppercase">Stop Doing This</th>
              <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-xs font-medium text-gray-500 uppercase">Why It Kills ROI</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="bg-white divide-y divide-gray-200">
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Weekly keyword pausing based on "no conversions"</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Reduces conversion volume, prevents AI from learning patterns</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Obsessing over Quality Score</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Smart Bidding makes QS less relevant; focus on conversion data quality instead</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Manual bid adjustments</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Overrides Smart Bidding, which adjusts bids better than humans</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-900">Fragmenting campaigns by match type</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-4 text-sm text-gray-700">Splits conversion volume, prevents AI from reaching learning threshold</td>
            </tr>
